  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) - An intergovernmental organization that sets international standards for preventing money laundering\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC)\n\n3. The Palermo Convention, which provides a framework for international cooperation against organized crime\n\n4. Basel Committee's guidelines on preventing criminal use of the banking system\n\n5. International Money Laundering Information Network (IMoLIN)\n\nMost countries have national laws implementing these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement anti-money laundering (AML) compliance programs\n\nThese laws require banks and financial institutions to monitor and report potential money laundering activities to help prevent financial crimes.",
